                    <head>Fragments of a copy of Breviarium Lincopense 1493</head>
                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc form="fragment">
                            <supportDesc>
                                <foliation>Modern foliation in pencil, 1-2.</foliation>
                                <collation>
                                    <formula>1-4(1).</formula>
                                </collation>
                            </supportDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <additions>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>Top left corner: in pencil by a modern hand, the current signum, <quote>A 127</quote>; centre of page: in ink by a modern hand, <quote>Ur ett exemplar af Breviarium Lincopense 1493</quote>.</note>
                            </p>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="false">
                                <p>Leaves contained in a piece of folded modern paper.</p>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100081">Sweden</placeName>
                                </origPlace>, <origDate notAfter="1600" notBefore="1551">16th century, second half</origDate>. The inclusion of of <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102642">Philip Melanchthon's</persName> hymn <foreign xml:lang="la">Dicimus grates tibi</foreign>, first printed in <date when="1543"/>, provides an approximate terminus post quem for this part of the fragment. The hymn <foreign xml:lang="la">Puer natus est</foreign> on <locus from="1v" to="2r" scheme="folios"/> with its Swedish translation was printed in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100078">Stockholm</placeName> in <date when="1572"/> (<bibl>
                                    <title ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107374">Then swenska psalmeboken</title>
                                    <citedRange from="69v" to="70v" unit="folio"/>
                                </bibl>), and the note at the top of <locus from="S3r" to="S3r" scheme="folios"/> gives the date of <date when="1573"/>, likely pushing the overall dating to around this time.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The note on <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/> states that the fragment was found in a copy of the <foreign xml:lang="la">Breviarium Lincopense</foreign> printed in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100286">Nuremberg</placeName> in <date when="1493">1493</date> but does not say where or when.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Acquisition date unknown.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
                    <msPart>
                        <msIdentifier>
                            <idno type="codicologicalUnit">1</idno>
                        </msIdentifier>
                        <msContents>
                            <textLang mainLang="la"/>
                            <msItem defective="true">
                                <locus from="1r" to="1v" scheme="folios"/>
                                <author>
                                    <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102642"> Philip Melanchthon </persName>
                                </author>
                                <title type="desc">Dicimus grates tibi (hymn)</title>
                                <incipit>Interim sed nos tegit angelorum</incipit>
                                <explicit>obsecramus pectore toto Amen</explicit>
                                <note>
                                    <p> The manuscript transmits the five last stanzas of <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102642">Philip Melanchthon</persName>'s hymn <foreign xml:lang="la">Dicimus grates tibi</foreign>, first printed in 1543 (<bibl>
                                            <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107370">Melanchthon (1543)</title>
                                        </bibl>); here, as printed in <bibl>
                                            <title type="uniform" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107369">Philippi Melanthonis Opera quae supersunt omnia</title>
                                            <citedRange from="10" to="10" unit="volume"/>
                                            <citedRange from="586" to="586" unit="column"/>
                                        </bibl>.</p>
                                    <p/>
                                    <p>
                                        <!--Till den som katalogiserar detta fragment: Texten på f. 1r-a är strof 7-11 (av totalt 11 strofer) av Melanchtons hymn "Dicimus grates tibi". Melanchton levde mellan 1497-1560, vilket hjälper till att datera just denna del av det som finns skrivet.(Erika) Om Melancthon föddes 1497 kan ju inte hans hymn vara del av Brev. Linc. 1493... Varken item 1 el 2 finns med i index till Brev. Linc.-->
                                    </p>
                                </note>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem>
                                <locus from="1v" to="2r" scheme="folios"/>
                                <title type="desc">Puer natus in Bethlehem (hymn)</title>
                                <incipit>Puer natus in Bethlehem in Bethlehem</incipit>
                                <explicit xml:lang="sv">Laudetur sancta trinitas trinitas Deo dicamus gratias Haleluia <lb/> thes wari pris i ewighett ewighett then heliga trefollighet haleluia </explicit>
                                <note> Latin hymn with the Swedish translation on alternating lines. The Latin hymn is known, in similar form, from the 14th century (<bibl>
                                        <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107372">Dreves (1886)</title>
                                        <citedRange from="164" to="164" unit="page"/>
                                        <citedRange from="178" to="178" unit="number"/>
                                    </bibl>). The hymn with its Swedish translation was printed in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100078">Stockholm</placeName> in 1572 (<bibl>
                                        <title ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107374">Then swenska psalmeboken</title>
                                        <citedRange from="69v" to="70v" unit="folio"/>
                                    </bibl>).</note>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem>
                                <locus from="2v" to="2v" scheme="folios"/>
                                <title type="desc">Instruction for the singing of the Kyrie</title>
                                <incipit>Sacratissima penthecostes die</incipit>
                                <explicit>kyrie de sancto spiritu minus <unclear quantity="3" unit="chars" reason="illegible"/> Aleluia Aleluia</explicit>
                                <note>
                                    <p> The folio transmits an instruction for which Kyrie to sing at which feast.</p>
                                    <p>
                                        <!--FInns det alltså olika: maius minus etc - Hittar inte Kyrie i index till Brev. Lic.-->
                                    </p>
                                </note>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem defective="true">
                                <locus from="S3r" to="S3r" scheme="folios"/>
                                <title type="desc">Instruction</title>
                                <rubric>Anno domini 1573 fuit (?)</rubric>
                                <incipit>
                                    <unclear quantity="5" unit="chars" reason="illegible"/> hyems in <unclear quantity="7" unit="chars" reason="illegible"/>
                                </incipit>
                                <explicit>Vide de primavera in breviari</explicit>
                                <note>The folio transmits an instruction for which Sunday is to be counted as the first of the month. The fragment is mounted on a piece of modern paper and the original verso therefore not visible.</note>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem>
                                <locus from="S4r" to="S4r" scheme="folios"/>
                                <title type="desc">The monk who would not pray his hours</title>
                                <rubric>De <unclear quantity="1" unit="chars"/>ndi Mona<supplied reason="damage">c</supplied>ho <!--Det är inte venerandi!--></rubric>
                                <incipit>
                                    <supplied reason="damage">E</supplied>rat olim quidam sacerdos in monaste<supplied reason="damage">rio</supplied>
                                </incipit>
                                <explicit>fac tibi horas canonicas</explicit>
                                <note>The fragment is mounted on a piece of modern paper and the original verso therefore not visible.</note>
                            </msItem>
                        </msContents>
